    "event-causal] causation\" (1983, p. 97), identifying it as an expression of the formal \"order that is there whenever actions are done with intentions\" (2000, p. 80).",
    "Where this order is discerned, it is because an extended region of the agent-centred causal network manifests certain features -it has a \"form of temporal unity\" (Lavin, 2015) characteristic of intentional action.",
    "Before getting to grips with these pronouncements, it might help to air an initial worry.",
    "While I've started to suggest that Anscombe's formal account of rationalisation is radically different to Davidson's causal story, someone might think that this conceptual distinction at the level of rationalisation has no direct bearing on the metaphysical debate about action.",
    "Discerning a formal order in events might also always involve (maybe tacitly) picking out a bodily movement as caused by a basic reason -the former might obtain just because the latter always occurs."
